TY  - JOUR
AB  - We integrate a widely accepted version of the separation of ownership and control-Michael Jensen's (1986) free cashflow theory-into a dynamic equilibrium model, and study the effect of imperfect corporate control on asset prices and investment. Aggregate free cashflow of the corporate sector is an important state variable in explaining asset prices, investment, and the cyclical behavior of interest rates and the yield curve. The financial friction causes cash-flow shocks to affect investment, and causes otherwise i.i.d. shocks to be transmitted from period to period. The shocks propagate through large firms and during booms.
